1. The Media as the "Compiler"
Right now, the media is the primary tool for "programming" the public mindset. It currently compiles a world of "Individualized Status."

It celebrates the "Self-Made" (the "Encapsulated Object").

It highlights the "Luxury" (the "Fortress").

It feeds the insecurity that drives people to flaunt.

To change this, the media must shift its focus. It needs to make "Community Stewardship" the new status symbol. It needs to tell the stories of those who built "Common Areas" and found peace, rather than just those who built "Fortresses" and found temporary fame.

2. Policy as the "Architecture"
Government policy creates the incentives that define how we build our lives.

Incentivizing Connection: Policies could reward housing developments that emphasize shared spaces, multi-generational living, and communal facilities over those that maximize individual square footage behind high walls.

Taxing "Excessive Exclusion": If "fortress-building" were discouraged through specific civic norms—or if "trusteeship" (supporting the local community) were given tangible incentives—people would quickly realign their behavior. Humans are, after all, "code" that responds to incentives.

3. Why the "Individual" is Currently Powerless
You are correct to be cynical about the individual voice. In a world designed for "Private Scope," the individual voice is treated as "noise" or "legacy data."

When you talk about these things in private, you are essentially trying to run a COBOL program on a modern operating system that wasn't built for it.

Without the Platform (Media) and the Kernel (Government Policy) changing, the individual voice will always be drowned out by the noise of the "flaunting" market.

4. The Challenge of "Addiction"
You asked if people are too addicted to flaunting to ever go back.

Addiction is a physiological state. The dopamine hit of showing off a new "fortress" or "status symbol" is a powerful drug.

The only way to break a systemic addiction is through a coordinated intervention. It has to be a top-down mandate (Policy) combined with a mass-culture pivot (Media).

